The Oceans'' was preceded by similar National Geographic productions: ''Drain the Great Lakes''''' , '''''Drain the Titanic'' and ''Drain the Bermuda Triangle'''''.'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/m04tvpay-20180718-h12uov.html|title=TV pick: Drain the Oceans|last=Houston|first=Melinda|date=2018-08-04|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref> The series is available in the form of a 10-part season and a 15-part season on iTunes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/tv-season/drain-the-oceans/id1383510675|title=Season 1 on iTunes}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/tv-season/drain-the-oceans-season-2/id1464200123|title=Season 2 on iTunes}}</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\n<onlyinclude>{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Episodes\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Cast\n!colspan=\"2\" |Originally aired\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"|First aired\n! scope=\"col\"|Last aired\n\n|-\n| 1\n| 25\n|\n| May 28, 2018\n| March 31, 2019\n\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:National Geographic Channel original programming]]\n[[Category:Australian documentary television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British documentary television series]]\n[[Category:2016 Australian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2016 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Television series by Electric Pictures]]\n\n\n{{Documentary-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Gildir", "label": "safe", "comment": "Deleted space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drain_the_Oceans"}
{"title_page": "REICK (DJ)", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name             = REICK\n| image            = https://s.mxmcdn.net/images-storage/albums5/1/8/9/1/3/0/46031981_500_500.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| birth_name       = Koushik Mukherjee\n| Genres           = Dance-Pop, Electronic\n| Alias            = Dj Koushik, REICK, Koushik Mukherjee\n| Instruments      = Keyboard, Piano, Synthesizer\n}}\n\n'''[Koushik Mukherjee]''' known professionally as '''[REICK]''' ''(previously went by the stage name Koushik Mukherjee)'' is an [[Indian people|Indian]] [[Disc jockey|DJ]], songwriter and record producer based in [[Kolkata]], [[India]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/koushik-mukherjee-mn0003582679/discography|title=Koushik Mukherjee {{!}} Album Discography|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/artist/4DPP90htu1QIrbeZ6g3OAs|title=REICK|website=Spotify|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> He is best known for his ability to create an unique vibe while performing or producing music. Some of his most popular tracks are \"'''[[Slow Love]]'''\" featuring [[Jimmy Burney]] , \"'''There For You'''\" which did turn out to be an important mark to begin his career as a record producer.\n\n== Career ==\nREICK has performed across the country at various clubs, music festivals alongside some of the finest Indian and international artists.\n\nHe has began his career interning with [[The Thrillseekers]] which did help him gain interest and perfect his art for electronic music.\n\nHe made his first official release '''\"There For You\"''' as Koushik Mukherjee which peaked onto #52 rank on Top 100 Electronica charts at [[Beatport]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/there-for-you-mw0003010771|title=There for You - Koushik Mukherjee {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beatport.com/artist/koushik-mukherjee/580276|title=Koushik Mukherjee Tracks & Releases on Beatport|website=www.beatport.com|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nSuccess came in as he dropped his new single '''[https://fanlink.to/reickmusic \"Slow Love\"]''' under his new stage name '''REICK'''. Slow Love garnered alot of attention with it peaking onto #2 rank on [[ITunes Store|iTunes]] India Dance Charts and #91 on iTunes India charts <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kworb.net/itunes/artist/reick.html|title=REICK Chart Positions on iTunes/Spotify/YouTube|website=kworb.net|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> within the first week of the release. Slow Love has over 1.1 Million views on [[YouTube (channel)|YouTube]]<ref>{{Citation|title=REICK ft. Jimmy Burney - Slow Love (Official Music Video)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9hqVWE8QEA0|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> , and is also being aired on [[VH1 India|Vh1]].\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== '''Singles''' ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Title             \n!Year\n!Album\n!Notes\n|-\n|\"Himalaya\" \ncredited as a co producer\n\nfo inDjnous Tribe along with Dj Harish <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beatport.com/track/himalaya-original-mix/4211508|title=Himalaya (Original Mix) by DJ Harish, Sid & Koushik, InDJnous Tribe on Beatport|website=www.beatport.com|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>    \n|2013  \n|Single \n|\n|-\n|\"There For You\"\ncredited as Koushik Mukherjee <ref>{{Citation|title=\u200eThere For You - Single by Koushik Mukherjee|url=https://music.apple.com/in/album/there-for-you-single/1161489482|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=There For You|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/0mArWEN2kSjLh5hrlCO96Q|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Koushik-Mukherjee-There-For-You/release/9436847|title=Koushik Mukherjee - There For You|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n|2016\n|Single  \n|Ranked #52 on Beaport Top 100 Electronica Charts\n|-\n|\"Slow Love\" feat. [[Jimmy Burney]] \ncredited as REICK <ref>{{Citation|title=Slow Love|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/6i2Zclop35JchX5Z83CVGi|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/in/artist/reick/1479322253|title=\u200eREICK on Apple Music|website=Apple Music|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://testicanzoni.mtv.it/testi-REICK_40242992/testo-Slow-Love-(Radio-Edit)-%5Bfeat.-Jimmy-Burney%5D-100393547|title=Slow Love (Radio Edit) [feat. Jimmy Burney] (Testo) - REICK|website=MTV Testi e Canzoni|language=it|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n|2019\n|Single\n|Ranked #2 on iTunes India (Dance Charts)\nRanked #91 on iTunes India Charts\n\n1.1+ Million Views on YouTube\n\nAiring on Vh1\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}  <!--- This makes all the footnotes list here --->\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* Coverage by [[The Telegraph (Kolkata)|The Telegraph]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/entertainment/winter-party-in-association-with-t2/cid/1414168|title=Winter Party in association with t2|website=www.telegraphindia.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/culture/t2-turned-11-this-year-and-we-dedicated-the-special-moment-to-you-mdash-the-t2-reader/cid/1383553|title=t2 turned 11 this year, and we dedicated the special moment to you \u2014 the t2 reader!|website=www.telegraphindia.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- Use the format: * [http://www.example.com/ example.com] -->\n\n* [https://open.spotify.com/artist/4DPP90htu1QIrbeZ6g3OAs REICK] on [[Spotify]]\n* [https://music.apple.com/in/artist/reick/1479322253 REICK] on [[iTunes]]\n* [https://www.jiosaavn.com/artist/reick-songs/LBCWi2icH9w_ REICK] on [[JioSaavn|Saavn]]\n* [https://soundcloud.com/reickmusic REICK] on [[Gaana]]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCykXADq156Byad9cNc6Wy6w REICK] on [[YouTube (channel)|YouTube]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name             = REICK\n| image            = https://s.mxmcdn.net/images-storage/albums5/1/8/9/1/3/0/46031981_500_500.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| birth_name       = Koushik Mukherjee\n| Genres           = Dance-Pop, Electronic\n| Alias            = Dj Koushik, REICK, Koushik Mukherjee\n| Instruments      = Keyboard, Piano, Synthesizer\n}}\n\n'''[Koushik Mukherjee]''' known professionally as '''[REICK]''' ''(previously went by the stage name Koushik Mukherjee)'' is an [[Indian people|Indian]] [[Disc jockey|DJ]], songwriter and record producer based in [[Kolkata]], [[India]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/koushik-mukherjee-mn0003582679/discography|title=Koushik Mukherjee {{!}} Album Discography|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/artist/4DPP90htu1QIrbeZ6g3OAs|title=REICK|website=Spotify|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> He is best known for his ability to create an unique vibe while performing or producing music. Some of his most popular tracks are \"'''Slow Love'''\" featuring [[Jimmy Burney]] , \"'''There For You'''\" which did turn out to be an important mark to begin his career as a record producer.\n\n== Career ==\nREICK has performed across the country at various clubs, music festivals alongside some of the finest Indian and international artists.\n\nHe has began his career interning with [[The Thrillseekers]] which did help him gain interest and perfect his art for electronic music.\n\nHe made his first official release '''\"There For You\"''' as Koushik Mukherjee which peaked onto #52 rank on Top 100 Electronica charts at [[Beatport]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/there-for-you-mw0003010771|title=There for You - Koushik Mukherjee {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beatport.com/artist/koushik-mukherjee/580276|title=Koushik Mukherjee Tracks & Releases on Beatport|website=www.beatport.com|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nSuccess came in as he dropped his new single '''[https://fanlink.to/reickmusic \"Slow Love\"]''' under his new stage name '''REICK'''. Slow Love garnered alot of attention with it peaking onto #2 rank on [[ITunes Store|iTunes]] India Dance Charts and #91 on iTunes India charts <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kworb.net/itunes/artist/reick.html|title=REICK Chart Positions on iTunes/Spotify/YouTube|website=kworb.net|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> within the first week of the release. Slow Love has over 1.1 Million views on [[YouTube (channel)|YouTube]]<ref>{{Citation|title=REICK ft. Jimmy Burney - Slow Love (Official Music Video)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9hqVWE8QEA0|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> , and is also being aired on [[VH1 India|Vh1]].\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== '''Singles''' ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Title             \n!Year\n!Album\n!Notes\n|-\n|\"Himalaya\" \ncredited as a co producer\n\nfo inDjnous Tribe along with Dj Harish <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beatport.com/track/himalaya-original-mix/4211508|title=Himalaya (Original Mix) by DJ Harish, Sid & Koushik, InDJnous Tribe on Beatport|website=www.beatport.com|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>    \n|2013  \n|Single \n|\n|-\n|\"There For You\"\ncredited as Koushik Mukherjee <ref>{{Citation|title=\u200eThere For You - Single by Koushik Mukherjee|url=https://music.apple.com/in/album/there-for-you-single/1161489482|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=There For You|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/0mArWEN2kSjLh5hrlCO96Q|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Koushik-Mukherjee-There-For-You/release/9436847|title=Koushik Mukherjee - There For You|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n|2016\n|Single  \n|Ranked #52 on Beaport Top 100 Electronica Charts\n|-\n|\"Slow Love\" feat. [[Jimmy Burney]] \ncredited as REICK <ref>{{Citation|title=Slow Love|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/6i2Zclop35JchX5Z83CVGi|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/in/artist/reick/1479322253|title=\u200eREICK on Apple Music|website=Apple Music|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://testicanzoni.mtv.it/testi-REICK_40242992/testo-Slow-Love-(Radio-Edit)-%5Bfeat.-Jimmy-Burney%5D-100393547|title=Slow Love (Radio Edit) [feat. Jimmy Burney] (Testo) - REICK|website=MTV Testi e Canzoni|language=it|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n|2019\n|Single\n|Ranked #2 on iTunes India (Dance Charts)\nRanked #91 on iTunes India Charts\n\n1.1+ Million Views on YouTube\n\nAiring on Vh1\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}  <!--- This makes all the footnotes list here --->\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* Coverage by [[The Telegraph (Kolkata)|The Telegraph]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/entertainment/winter-party-in-association-with-t2/cid/1414168|title=Winter Party in association with t2|website=www.telegraphindia.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/culture/t2-turned-11-this-year-and-we-dedicated-the-special-moment-to-you-mdash-the-t2-reader/cid/1383553|title=t2 turned 11 this year, and we dedicated the special moment to you \u2014 the t2 reader!|website=www.telegraphindia.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- Use the format: * [http://www.example.com/ example.com] -->\n\n* [https://open.spotify.com/artist/4DPP90htu1QIrbeZ6g3OAs REICK] on [[Spotify]]\n* [https://music.apple.com/in/artist/reick/1479322253 REICK] on [[iTunes]]\n* [https://www.jiosaavn.com/artist/reick-songs/LBCWi2icH9w_ REICK] on [[JioSaavn|Saavn]]\n* [https://soundcloud.com/reickmusic REICK] on [[Gaana]]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCykXADq156Byad9cNc6Wy6w REICK] on [[YouTube (channel)|YouTube]]\n", "name_user": "Partyshaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/REICK_(DJ)"}
{"title_page": "Rediffusion", "text_new": "{{short description|Radio and television company}}\n{{about|the original radio and television wired relay company|the related TV stations and other businesses|Rediffusion (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2012}}In the hurly burly of commercial life, and fall out on the high street, the Rediffusion brand and the TV channels disappeared in the 1990s \u2013 momentarily. It has been brought back to life by business management expert Ken Helps. \n\nFamous British electrical consumer appliance trademark brand, Rediffusion has \u00a0completed its first licencing deal with a consortium of Chinese companies.\n\nRediffusion, based in Bristol has completed it\u2019s a 5-year licencing deal with a consortium of Chinese companies, led by East-Innovation Brand Management Co. Ltd.\n\n''The  Rediffusion's brand\u2019s distinct British heritage is very well received in emerging global markets, especially in China and South East Asia. Brands like Nokia, Nintendo, Polaroid, Kodak and Harley Davidson, that have successfully launched new product lines to capitalise on nostalgic consumers, to see that there is a promising future for retro branding.''{{Refimprove|date=July 2013}}\n'''Rediffusion''' was a business that distributed radio and TV signals through wired relay networks.  The business gave rise to a number of other companies, including [[Associated-Rediffusion]], later known as Rediffusion London, one of the first companies to win a terrestrial [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] ([[commercial television]]) franchise in the [[UK]]. Rediffusion also spawned a record label, Rediffusion International Music, in 1968. Redifon was the name used until 1981 for companies in the capital goods businesses of Rediffusion, viz. Redifon Computers, Redifon Flight Simulation and Redifon Telecommunications.\n\n==Early history==\nRediffusion was the trading name of '''Broadcast Relay Service''' Ltd, formed in 1928.  In 1929 the company introduced its first cable radio service in [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]] to customers frustrated with the difficulties of tuning in weak radio broadcasts. In the customer premises, nothing more than a selector switch and loudspeaker were needed.  Initially, the service consisted primarily of rebroadcasts of the [[BBC Radio]] service, which was reflected in the trading name: Rediffusion simply means \"broadcasting again\".\n\nRediffusion quickly branched out into making, renting, and selling radios, both receivers for its cable services and conventional models. With the arrival of the first experimental [[television]] broadcasts in the 1930s, Rediffusion began manufacturing TV sets and supplying \"Piped TV\", an early form of [[cable TV]], service to its customers, until the cessation of television broadcasts during the [[Second World War]].\n\nThe first British colony to have the Rediffusion service was [[Barbados]] in 1934, when Radio Distribution (Barbados) Limited was formed.\n\nA year later, Rediffusion started operating in [[Malta]]. Transmissions in Malta started from [[Hamrun]] on 11 November 1935 under the name of \"Broadcast Relay Service Malta Ltd.\" Charles Whotcroft and George Powler were the first manager and chief engineer respectively.<ref>Ix-Xandir F'Malta, Remig Sacco, Malta 1985, 24.</ref>\n\n==Post-war==\nIn 1947 [[British Electric Traction]] acquired a substantial minority interest in Rediffusion.  BET acquired a controlling interest in 1967, and the remaining 36% of equity in 1983.<ref>[http://www.competition-commission.org.uk/rep_pub/reports/1985/fulltext/184c03.pdf Competition Commission report, 1985] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071025074653/http://www.competition-commission.org.uk//rep_pub/reports/1985/fulltext/184c03.pdf |date=25 October 2007 }}  The assertion on some websites that BET controlled Rediffusion from its inception does not appear to be right.</ref>\n\nIn 1948 Rediffusion established '''Redifon Ltd''' as a manufacturer of naval (and later flight) telecommunications equipment.\n\nAfter the war, Rediffusion began operations in several of the then British colonies. These included holding the concessions for wired and over-the-air radio and television stations. A subsidiary company, '''Overseas Rediffusion''', operated these stations and also sold advertising time and programming for them. Stations included the radio station Rediffusion [[Starcom Network|Barbados]],<ref>http://www.onecaribbeanmedia.net/media_group.php?mid=26</ref> [[Rediffusion Television|Hong Kong]], [[Rediffusion Singapore|Singapore]], [[Red FM (Malaysia)|Malaysia]], Thailand and the wired television service Rediffusion Television in [[Hong Kong]], the latter later known as [[Asia Television]]. It also opened a company in Jersey in 1949, Rediffusion (Channel Islands) Limited, which obtained a licence to relay radio broadcasts from the [[States of Jersey]] in 1950. It also opened a manufacturing division in Jersey, Television Research Limited (TVR) which also provided research facilities for the wired network. This was established in 1952 and was renamed Reditronics Limited in 1976.\n\nBET's financial resources enabled Rediffusion to capitalise on the growth in post war television, which restarted in 1946. Initially, the company installed cable TV systems in blocks of flats in London, and over the next few years expanded outside London.  The company was also involved in the sale and rental of television sets.\n\n==Expansion into broadcasting==\nWith the passage of the [[Television Act 1954]], Rediffusion joined forces with [[Associated Newspapers]], a subsidiary of [[Daily Mail and General Trust]], to form [[Associated-Rediffusion]], and won the coveted London weekday [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] broadcast franchise. They began broadcasting on 22 September 1955.\n\nDuring the partnership's first year, Associated-Rediffusion was losing money so fast that \nby the end of 1956, Associated Newspapers sold 80% of its stake back to BET and Rediffusion at a severe loss. Around this time, Associated-Rediffusion struck a very  lucrative deal with [[Granada Television]], the franchise holder for weekday broadcasts in the North of England. Granada was also losing money, and lacked the financial resources of BET; the deal guaranteed Granada a certain level of financial security, at the cost of Associated-Rediffusion receiving the vast majority of future profits from their arrangement.\n\nOn 29 September 1962 Rediffusion (Malta) Ltd. inaugurated a television service covering the [[Malta|Maltese]] islands.<ref name=\"PSB\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8bwlvxicNw0C&lpg=PA245&ots=npMqQD1-qu&dq=rediffusion%20malta%20television&pg=PA245#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Public Service Broadcasting in the Age of Globalization''], Indrajit Banerjee, Kalinga Seneviratne, AMIC, 2006, page 245</ref> \n\nBy 1964, when Associated-Rediffusion changed its name to Rediffusion London, the efforts of the owners had left them sitting on a substantial cash pile, and it is arguable that this success may have led to the 1967 decision by the [[Independent Television Authority]] to effectively break up the company. Rediffusion London was ordered to merge with [[Associated British Corporation]], the holder of the weekend [[English Midlands|Midlands]] and North of England franchises, to form [[Thames Television]], with ABC given the controlling interest (despite its generally weaker financial position) and Rediffusion holding 49%. Thames Television was given the new weekday London franchise, with ABC's existing franchises awarded to other companies.\n\n==Other ventures==\n===Rediffusion Cable===\n[[File:Antique Barbados Rediffusion stereo-001.jpg|thumb|Long deactivated speaker for the Rediffusion located at the police station in Hastings, [[Christ Church, Barbados]].]]\nRediffusion also offered a low-bandwidth cable TV and radio distribution system. This was based on connecting homes with multiple twisted-pair cables. Each pair carried a single TV or radio channel. The system was provided in most UK towns.  Selection of TV or radio station was by means of a rotary switch, usually mounted on a wall or window frame close to the point of entry of the cable into the home. From this a two-wire cable led to the TV or radio. The TVs used on this system were stripped-down TV sets with no tuner or RF front-end and the radios were little more than a loudspeaker with built in amplifier. Rediffusion abandoned this system of TV and radio distribution by the end of the 1980s.  The wall mounted switches, external junction boxes and street cable ducts are still visible in places that have not been redeveloped since the late 1980s.\n\n===Overseas Rediffusion===\n[[File:Piet\u00e0 Malta Buildings 19.jpg|thumb| Ex-[[Rediffusion House]] [[Malta]] now known as P.B.S Creativity Hub in [[Gwardaman\u0121a]], built for Rediffusion (Malta) Ltd in 1958]]\n\nBET and Rediffusion Limited had strong links with the former British colonies. These included holding the concessions for wired and over-the-air radio and television stations. A subsidiary company, Overseas Rediffusion, operated these stations and also sold advertising time and programming for them. Stations included the radio operations in [[List of radio stations in Barbados#Defunct|Barbados]],<ref>[http://www.starcomnetwork.net/aboutus/index.htm starcomnetwork.net/aboutus] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090901192633/http://www.starcomnetwork.net/aboutus/index.htm |date=1 September 2009 }}</ref> [[Sierra Leone Broadcasting Corporation|Sierra Leone]], [[Rediffusion Singapore|Singapore]], [[Red FM (Malaysia)|Malaysia]], [[Public Broadcasting Services|Malta]], Thailand and the wired television service [[Rediffusion Television]] in [[Hong Kong]], the latter now known as [[Asia Television]].\n\n===Rediffusion Rentals===\nThe Rediffusion retail chain, renting and servicing TVs, radios, VCRs and hi-fi systems, was common on high streets until it was bought by [[Granada Ltd.|Granada Rentals]] in 1984.\n\n==Last years==\nRediffusion's television sale and rental operations continued to grow, particularly following the start of colour television broadcasts in 1967.\n\nOn 14 February 1975 the employees of the Rediffusion (Malta) Ltd staged a sit-in strike at the company's premises in Malta<ref>Ix-xandir F'Malta, Tony C. Cutajar, Malta 2001, 63.</ref> and they even started to run the company.<ref>''The Untruth Game'', Francis Zammit Dimech, Malta 1986, 94.</ref> On 30 July 1975 an agreement was reached between Rediffusion Group of Companies and the [[Dom Mintoff]] led [[Labour Party (Malta)|Labour Party]] government of Malta for the transfer of all Rediffusion's assets in Malta to the Maltese government.<ref>''The Untruth Game'', Francis Zammit Dimech, Malta 1986, 95.</ref>\n\nThe company also experimented with its local cable operations:  a local community station in Bristol (\"Bristol Channel\") from 1973 to 1976, and an optical fibre system in Hastings in 1976.\n\nThe Rediffusion brand was also a name in [[flight simulator|aircraft simulation]] in both the UK and the US.  Redifon, established in 1948, had become a manufacturer of flight simulators and in 1981 BET changed Redifon's name to [[Thales Training & Simulation|Rediffusion Simulation]] to capitalise on the name.  The company was sold in 1988 to [[Hughes Aircraft]], which kept the Rediffusion name until it sold the company in 1994.\n\nRedifon (later Rediffusion) Computers was also part of the group and was based in [[Crawley]], [[West Sussex]]. It initially started in the production of analogue computers to control [[flight simulator]]s, then moved to produce minicomputers (\"R range\"), departmental Unix Servers and microcomputers (\"teleputers\"), specialising in data capture, enterprise accounting for local government and [[videotex]] systems. [[Michael Aldrich]] joined the company as Marketing Director in 1977 and became Managing Director and CEO in 1980. In 1979 Aldrich invented [[online shopping]] a form of [[electronic commerce]].<ref>Pioneers of Online Shopping, Aldrich Archive, University of Brighton http://www.aldricharchive.com</ref>\n\nFrom 1980 the company designed, manufactured, sold, installed and maintained online shopping systems mainly in the UK and achieved a significant number of world firsts. The company\u2019s name was changed to Rediffusion Computers in 1981. During the 1980s a large part of the company's revenue came from its sales in Eastern Europe and Russia. Equipment that met the CoCom directive for the sales of high performance technology to the Soviet Block was supplied to a number of customers the largest of which was [[Gazprom]] who used the systems on the Siberian Gas Pipeline project.<ref>USSR, Aldrich Archive, University of Brighton http://www.aldricharchive.com</ref> In addition there was a steady stream of Polish engineers attending the Crawley training facility to enable them to support and maintain this equipment mainly in Russia but also in other countries in the [[Eastern Bloc]].\n\nThe company was highly innovative and amongst other things developed a signature recognition system for detecting [[cheque fraud]].  It was one of the first companies to sell a turnkey solution that utilised the newly available Post Office database (PAF) for postcode recognition. In 1984 Aldrich led a [[management buyout]] and the company became ''ROCC Computers'' (Rediffusion's Old Computer Company). Aldrich was the largest shareholder and he subsequently bought-out the other shareholders.\n\nIn the 1980s, Rediffusion's cable operations were left behind by the new generation of [[cable TV]] networks.  BET (from 1983 the sole owners of Rediffusion) began divesting and sold off its overseas interests, and at the end of the 1980s the company was broken up,  The rentals business went to [[Granada Ltd.|Granada]], and the cable network systems were sold to the [[Robert Maxwell|Maxwell Communications]].\n\nReditronics Jersey was sold to SCK Holdings Limited in 1986 and following BET's retreat from cable and the consequent loss of associated contracts, it ceased trading in 1987. The Rediffusion Jersey cable network was sold to Jersey Cable Limited (now [[Newtel Solutions]]) in 1988.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Associated-Rediffusion]]\n* [[Rediffusion Singapore]]\n* [[Rediffusion Television]] (Hong Kong)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.rediffusion.info The history of Rediffusion by Gerald K Clode]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120218231748/http://www.transdiffusion.org/tmc/tvh/history/history.php A history of Rediffusion by Russ J Graham]\n*[http://www.petford.net/kaleidoscope/itv-history.html Shuffling the pack by Simon Coward (1993-94)]\n*[http://www.prx205.org/docs/Rediffusion%20Jersey.pdf History of Radio and Television Relay Services in Jersey]\n*[http://www.7tt77.co.uk/REDIFFUSION.html Rediffusion International Music]\n*[http://www.rediffusion.info/Barbados/ Rediffusion Barbados] (unofficial history site)\n\n[[Category:Defunct media companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies of Malta]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Radio and television company}}\n{{about|the original radio and television wired relay company|the related TV stations and other businesses|Rediffusion (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2012}}\n{{Refimprove|date=July 2013}}\n'''Rediffusion''' was a business that distributed radio and TV signals through wired relay networks.  The business gave rise to a number of other companies, including [[Associated-Rediffusion]], later known as Rediffusion London, one of the first companies to win a terrestrial [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] ([[commercial television]]) franchise in the [[UK]]. Rediffusion also spawned a record label, Rediffusion International Music, in 1968. Redifon was the name used until 1981 for companies in the capital goods businesses of Rediffusion, viz. Redifon Computers, Redifon Flight Simulation and Redifon Telecommunications.\n\n==Early history==\nRediffusion was the trading name of '''Broadcast Relay Service''' Ltd, formed in 1928.  In 1929 the company introduced its first cable radio service in [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]] to customers frustrated with the difficulties of tuning in weak radio broadcasts. In the customer premises, nothing more than a selector switch and loudspeaker were needed.  Initially, the service consisted primarily of rebroadcasts of the [[BBC Radio]] service, which was reflected in the trading name: Rediffusion simply means \"broadcasting again\".\n\nRediffusion quickly branched out into making, renting, and selling radios, both receivers for its cable services and conventional models. With the arrival of the first experimental [[television]] broadcasts in the 1930s, Rediffusion began manufacturing TV sets and supplying \"Piped TV\", an early form of [[cable TV]], service to its customers, until the cessation of television broadcasts during the [[Second World War]].\n\nThe first British colony to have the Rediffusion service was [[Barbados]] in 1934, when Radio Distribution (Barbados) Limited was formed.\n\nA year later, Rediffusion started operating in [[Malta]]. Transmissions in Malta started from [[Hamrun]] on 11 November 1935 under the name of \"Broadcast Relay Service Malta Ltd.\" Charles Whotcroft and George Powler were the first manager and chief engineer respectively.<ref>Ix-Xandir F'Malta, Remig Sacco, Malta 1985, 24.</ref>\n\n==Post-war==\nIn 1947 [[British Electric Traction]] acquired a substantial minority interest in Rediffusion.  BET acquired a controlling interest in 1967, and the remaining 36% of equity in 1983.<ref>[http://www.competition-commission.org.uk/rep_pub/reports/1985/fulltext/184c03.pdf Competition Commission report, 1985] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071025074653/http://www.competition-commission.org.uk//rep_pub/reports/1985/fulltext/184c03.pdf |date=25 October 2007 }}  The assertion on some websites that BET controlled Rediffusion from its inception does not appear to be right.</ref>\n\nIn 1948 Rediffusion established '''Redifon Ltd''' as a manufacturer of naval (and later flight) telecommunications equipment.\n\nAfter the war, Rediffusion began operations in several of the then British colonies. These included holding the concessions for wired and over-the-air radio and television stations. A subsidiary company, '''Overseas Rediffusion''', operated these stations and also sold advertising time and programming for them. Stations included the radio station Rediffusion [[Starcom Network|Barbados]],<ref>http://www.onecaribbeanmedia.net/media_group.php?mid=26</ref> [[Rediffusion Television|Hong Kong]], [[Rediffusion Singapore|Singapore]], [[Red FM (Malaysia)|Malaysia]], Thailand and the wired television service Rediffusion Television in [[Hong Kong]], the latter later known as [[Asia Television]]. It also opened a company in Jersey in 1949, Rediffusion (Channel Islands) Limited, which obtained a licence to relay radio broadcasts from the [[States of Jersey]] in 1950. It also opened a manufacturing division in Jersey, Television Research Limited (TVR) which also provided research facilities for the wired network. This was established in 1952 and was renamed Reditronics Limited in 1976.\n\nBET's financial resources enabled Rediffusion to capitalise on the growth in post war television, which restarted in 1946. Initially, the company installed cable TV systems in blocks of flats in London, and over the next few years expanded outside London.  The company was also involved in the sale and rental of television sets.\n\n==Expansion into broadcasting==\nWith the passage of the [[Television Act 1954]], Rediffusion joined forces with [[Associated Newspapers]], a subsidiary of [[Daily Mail and General Trust]], to form [[Associated-Rediffusion]], and won the coveted London weekday [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] broadcast franchise. They began broadcasting on 22 September 1955.\n\nDuring the partnership's first year, Associated-Rediffusion was losing money so fast that \nby the end of 1956, Associated Newspapers sold 80% of its stake back to BET and Rediffusion at a severe loss. Around this time, Associated-Rediffusion struck a very  lucrative deal with [[Granada Television]], the franchise holder for weekday broadcasts in the North of England. Granada was also losing money, and lacked the financial resources of BET; the deal guaranteed Granada a certain level of financial security, at the cost of Associated-Rediffusion receiving the vast majority of future profits from their arrangement.\n\nOn 29 September 1962 Rediffusion (Malta) Ltd. inaugurated a television service covering the [[Malta|Maltese]] islands.<ref name=\"PSB\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8bwlvxicNw0C&lpg=PA245&ots=npMqQD1-qu&dq=rediffusion%20malta%20television&pg=PA245#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Public Service Broadcasting in the Age of Globalization''], Indrajit Banerjee, Kalinga Seneviratne, AMIC, 2006, page 245</ref> \n\nBy 1964, when Associated-Rediffusion changed its name to Rediffusion London, the efforts of the owners had left them sitting on a substantial cash pile, and it is arguable that this success may have led to the 1967 decision by the [[Independent Television Authority]] to effectively break up the company. Rediffusion London was ordered to merge with [[Associated British Corporation]], the holder of the weekend [[English Midlands|Midlands]] and North of England franchises, to form [[Thames Television]], with ABC given the controlling interest (despite its generally weaker financial position) and Rediffusion holding 49%. Thames Television was given the new weekday London franchise, with ABC's existing franchises awarded to other companies.\n\n==Other ventures==\n===Rediffusion Cable===\n[[File:Antique Barbados Rediffusion stereo-001.jpg|thumb|Long deactivated speaker for the Rediffusion located at the police station in Hastings, [[Christ Church, Barbados]].]]\nRediffusion also offered a low-bandwidth cable TV and radio distribution system. This was based on connecting homes with multiple twisted-pair cables. Each pair carried a single TV or radio channel. The system was provided in most UK towns.  Selection of TV or radio station was by means of a rotary switch, usually mounted on a wall or window frame close to the point of entry of the cable into the home. From this a two-wire cable led to the TV or radio. The TVs used on this system were stripped-down TV sets with no tuner or RF front-end and the radios were little more than a loudspeaker with built in amplifier. Rediffusion abandoned this system of TV and radio distribution by the end of the 1980s.  The wall mounted switches, external junction boxes and street cable ducts are still visible in places that have not been redeveloped since the late 1980s.\n\n===Overseas Rediffusion===\n[[File:Piet\u00e0 Malta Buildings 19.jpg|thumb| Ex-[[Rediffusion House]] [[Malta]] now known as P.B.S Creativity Hub in [[Gwardaman\u0121a]], built for Rediffusion (Malta) Ltd in 1958]]\n\nBET and Rediffusion Limited had strong links with the former British colonies. These included holding the concessions for wired and over-the-air radio and television stations. A subsidiary company, Overseas Rediffusion, operated these stations and also sold advertising time and programming for them. Stations included the radio operations in [[List of radio stations in Barbados#Defunct|Barbados]],<ref>[http://www.starcomnetwork.net/aboutus/index.htm starcomnetwork.net/aboutus] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090901192633/http://www.starcomnetwork.net/aboutus/index.htm |date=1 September 2009 }}</ref> [[Sierra Leone Broadcasting Corporation|Sierra Leone]], [[Rediffusion Singapore|Singapore]], [[Red FM (Malaysia)|Malaysia]], [[Public Broadcasting Services|Malta]], Thailand and the wired television service [[Rediffusion Television]] in [[Hong Kong]], the latter now known as [[Asia Television]].\n\n===Rediffusion Rentals===\nThe Rediffusion retail chain, renting and servicing TVs, radios, VCRs and hi-fi systems, was common on high streets until it was bought by [[Granada Ltd.|Granada Rentals]] in 1984.\n\n==Last years==\nRediffusion's television sale and rental operations continued to grow, particularly following the start of colour television broadcasts in 1967.\n\nOn 14 February 1975 the employees of the Rediffusion (Malta) Ltd staged a sit-in strike at the company's premises in Malta<ref>Ix-xandir F'Malta, Tony C. Cutajar, Malta 2001, 63.</ref> and they even started to run the company.<ref>''The Untruth Game'', Francis Zammit Dimech, Malta 1986, 94.</ref> On 30 July 1975 an agreement was reached between Rediffusion Group of Companies and the [[Dom Mintoff]] led [[Labour Party (Malta)|Labour Party]] government of Malta for the transfer of all Rediffusion's assets in Malta to the Maltese government.<ref>''The Untruth Game'', Francis Zammit Dimech, Malta 1986, 95.</ref>\n\nThe company also experimented with its local cable operations:  a local community station in Bristol (\"Bristol Channel\") from 1973 to 1976, and an optical fibre system in Hastings in 1976.\n\nThe Rediffusion brand was also a name in [[flight simulator|aircraft simulation]] in both the UK and the US.  Redifon, established in 1948, had become a manufacturer of flight simulators and in 1981 BET changed Redifon's name to [[Thales Training & Simulation|Rediffusion Simulation]] to capitalise on the name.  The company was sold in 1988 to [[Hughes Aircraft]], which kept the Rediffusion name until it sold the company in 1994.\n\nRedifon (later Rediffusion) Computers was also part of the group and was based in [[Crawley]], [[West Sussex]]. It initially started in the production of analogue computers to control [[flight simulator]]s, then moved to produce minicomputers (\"R range\"), departmental Unix Servers and microcomputers (\"teleputers\"), specialising in data capture, enterprise accounting for local government and [[videotex]] systems. [[Michael Aldrich]] joined the company as Marketing Director in 1977 and became Managing Director and CEO in 1980. In 1979 Aldrich invented [[online shopping]] a form of [[electronic commerce]].<ref>Pioneers of Online Shopping, Aldrich Archive, University of Brighton http://www.aldricharchive.com</ref>\n\nFrom 1980 the company designed, manufactured, sold, installed and maintained online shopping systems mainly in the UK and achieved a significant number of world firsts. The company\u2019s name was changed to Rediffusion Computers in 1981. During the 1980s a large part of the company's revenue came from its sales in Eastern Europe and Russia. Equipment that met the CoCom directive for the sales of high performance technology to the Soviet Block was supplied to a number of customers the largest of which was [[Gazprom]] who used the systems on the Siberian Gas Pipeline project.<ref>USSR, Aldrich Archive, University of Brighton http://www.aldricharchive.com</ref> In addition there was a steady stream of Polish engineers attending the Crawley training facility to enable them to support and maintain this equipment mainly in Russia but also in other countries in the [[Eastern Bloc]].\n\nThe company was highly innovative and amongst other things developed a signature recognition system for detecting [[cheque fraud]].  It was one of the first companies to sell a turnkey solution that utilised the newly available Post Office database (PAF) for postcode recognition. In 1984 Aldrich led a [[management buyout]] and the company became ''ROCC Computers'' (Rediffusion's Old Computer Company). Aldrich was the largest shareholder and he subsequently bought-out the other shareholders.\n\nIn the 1980s, Rediffusion's cable operations were left behind by the new generation of [[cable TV]] networks.  BET (from 1983 the sole owners of Rediffusion) began divesting and sold off its overseas interests, and at the end of the 1980s the company was broken up,  The rentals business went to [[Granada Ltd.|Granada]], and the cable network systems were sold to the [[Robert Maxwell|Maxwell Communications]].\n\nReditronics Jersey was sold to SCK Holdings Limited in 1986 and following BET's retreat from cable and the consequent loss of associated contracts, it ceased trading in 1987. The Rediffusion Jersey cable network was sold to Jersey Cable Limited (now [[Newtel Solutions]]) in 1988.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Associated-Rediffusion]]\n* [[Rediffusion Singapore]]\n* [[Rediffusion Television]] (Hong Kong)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.rediffusion.info The history of Rediffusion by Gerald K Clode]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120218231748/http://www.transdiffusion.org/tmc/tvh/history/history.php A history of Rediffusion by Russ J Graham]\n*[http://www.petford.net/kaleidoscope/itv-history.html Shuffling the pack by Simon Coward (1993-94)]\n*[http://www.prx205.org/docs/Rediffusion%20Jersey.pdf History of Radio and Television Relay Services in Jersey]\n*[http://www.7tt77.co.uk/REDIFFUSION.html Rediffusion International Music]\n*[http://www.rediffusion.info/Barbados/ Rediffusion Barbados] (unofficial history site)\n\n[[Category:Defunct media companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies of Malta]]\n", "name_user": "KHelpsy", "label": "safe", "comment": "New update on Rediffusion", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rediffusion"}
{"title_page": "Audi A3", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Audi A3\n| image = 2018 Audi A3 Sport TDi Saloon 1.5 Front.jpg\n| caption = The facelift 3rd generation Audi A3 Saloon (8V, UK)\n| manufacturer = [[Audi|Audi AG]]\n| production = 1996\u2013present\n| Designer = David Caffrey\n| class = [[Compact executive car|Subcompact executive car]] ([[C-segment|C]])\n| body_style = 3 or 5-door [[hatchback]]\n| layout = [[Front-engine, front-wheel-drive layout|Front-engine, front-wheel-drive]] / [[Front-engine, four-wheel-drive layout|four-wheel-drive]] ([[quattro (four-wheel-drive system)|quattro]])\n| platform = [[Volkswagen Group A platform]]<br/>[[Volkswagen Group MQB platform]]\n| transmission = \n| sp = uk\n| Engine = 3.2L V12\n}}\n\nThe '''Audi A3''' is a [[Small family car|small family]] or [[Compact executive car|subcompact executive car]] manufactured and marketed since the 1990s<ref>[https://www.audi-mediacenter.com/en/press-releases/audi-a3-a-model-of-success-two-decades-three-generations-7134 Audi A3 a model of success: Two decades, three generations\"] (2 December 2016).  ''Audi-MediaCenter.com''.  Retrieved 24 December 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.autoevolution.com/audi/a3/ \"Audi A3: Generations Timeline, Specs, and Pictures\"] (28 October 2016).  ''AutoEvolution.com''.  Retrieved 11 January 2020.</ref> by the Audi subdivision of the [[Volkswagen Group]], now in its 3rd generation.\n\nThe first two generations of the Audi A3 were based on the [[Volkswagen Group A platform]], which they share with the [[Audi TT]], [[Volkswagen Golf]], [[Volkswagen Caddy]], and [[Volkswagen Touran]], as well as [[SEAT Le\u00f3n]], [[SEAT Toledo]], and [[\u0160koda Octavia]].\n\nThe third-generation A3 uses the [[Volkswagen Group MQB platform]].\n\n=={{Anchor|Mk1|8L}}First generation (''Typ'' 8L; 1996\u20132003)==\n{{unreferenced section|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n|name = First generation (8L)\n|image = Audi_A3_front_20080326.jpg\n|caption = Audi A3 5-door (post-facelift)\n|aka =\n|production = 1996\u20132003\n|designer = [[Dirk van Braeckel]] (1992)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bentleymotors.com/world_of_bentley/exhibitions/an_unbroken_line_exhibition/the_team/ |title=Bentley Motors Website : World of Bentley : Exhibitions : 'An Unbroken Line' Exhibition : The Team |publisher=Bentleymotors.com |date= |accessdate=21 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/2005-05-29/dirk-van-braeckel |title=Dirk van Braeckel |publisher=Businessweek |date=29 May 2005 |accessdate=21 February 2013}}</ref>\n|assembly = {{Unbulleted list |Germany: [[Ingolstadt]] (1996\u20132003) |Brazil: [[Curitiba]] ([[Volkswagen do Brasil]], 2000\u20132006)}}\n|body_style = 3-door [[hatchback]]<br/>5-door [[hatchback]]\n|platform = [[Volkswagen Group A platform#PQ34|Volkswagen Group A4 (PQ34)]]\n|engine = Petrol engine<br/ >{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = I4\n|1 = [[List of discontinued Volkswagen Group petrol engines#1.6 R4 74-75kW|1.6]]&nbsp;L\n|2 = [[List of discontinued Volkswagen Group petrol engines#1.8 R4 20v 92kW|1.8]]&nbsp;L [[multi-valve|20v]]\n|3 = [[List of Volkswagen Group petrol engines#1.8 R4 20vT|1.8]]&nbsp;L 20v Turbo\n}}\nDiesel engine<br/ >{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Inline-four\n|1 = [[List of Volkswagen Group diesel engines#1.9 R4 TDI PD 43-118kW|1.9]]&nbsp;L [[Turbocharged Direct Injection|TDI]]\n}}\n|transmission ={{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Manual transmission \n|1 = 5-speed [[Manual transmission|Manual]]\n|2 = 6-speed [[Manual transmission|Manual]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Automatic transmission\n|1 = 4-speed [[Automatic transmission|Automatic]]\n|2 = 5-speed [[Automatic transmission|Automatic]]\n}}\n|wheelbase = A3 {{convert|2513|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<br/>quattro & S3: {{convert|2519|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|length = A3 {{convert|4152|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<br/>S3 {{convert|4159|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|width = A3 {{convert|1735|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<br/>S3 {{convert|1763|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|height = A3 {{convert|1423|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<br/>S3 {{convert|1415|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|related = [[Volkswagen Golf#Golf Mk4 (A4/Typ 1J, 1997\u20132004)|Volkswagen Golf]] Mk4<br/>[[SEAT Le\u00f3n#1M|SEAT Le\u00f3n]] Mk1\n|sp = uk\n}}\n\nThe original A3 (or ''Type'' 8L) was introduced in the European market in 1996, marking Audi's return to the production of smaller cars following the demise of the [[Audi 50]] in 1978. This was the first [[Volkswagen Group]] model to use the \"PQ34\" or \"A4\" [[Automobile platform|platform]], bearing a close resemblance to the contemporary [[Volkswagen Golf Mk4]], which arrived a year later. Within three years, this platform was used for total of seven cars.\n\nThe A3 was initially available only with a three-door [[hatchback]] body, to present a more sporty image than the Golf, in both [[front-wheel drive|front]] and [[four-wheel drive]]. The [[inline-four engine|inline four-cylinder]] engines were [[transverse engine|transversely mounted]]. The Audi A3 was the eighth model in the Audi lineup to use five valves per cylinder.\n\nThe United Kingdom market first received the Audi A3 in November 1996.\n\nIn 1999, Audi expanded the range with the introduction of more powerful versions: a 1.8 turbo rated {{convert|180|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}, and a 1.9 [[Turbocharged Direct Injection|TDI]] [[diesel engine]] with [[unit injector]] \"Pumpe D\u00fcse\" (PD) technology and [[variable geometry turbocharger]]. The four-wheel-drive A3 1.8T [[quattro (four-wheel-drive system)|quattro]] used either the {{convert|150|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} or {{convert|180|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} engine, and the same [[Haldex Traction]]-based four-wheel-drive system as the [[Audi S3]] and the [[Audi TT]]. Also in 1999, Audi also introduced a five-door body.\n\nIn late 2000, the A3 range was revised with new headlights and rear lamps, other minor cosmetic changes, an improved interior, and the introduction of a six-speed [[manual transmission|manual]] gearbox, on the {{convert|180|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} 1.8 Turbo and the new {{convert|130|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} 1.9 TDI.\n\nAudi's [[electronic stability control]], traction-control, and brake force distribution computer became standard equipment in some countries.\n\nAlthough the first-generation Audi A3 was replaced in Europe in 2003, the first generation model continued to be sold in some markets. Production of the first generation model stopped in Brazil in 2006.\n\n{{gallery\n| width = 160\n| height = 100\n|File:1997 Audi A3 1.6 Front.jpg|Audi A3 3-door (pre-facelift)\n|File:1997 Audi A3 1.6 Rear.jpg|Audi A3 3-door (pre-facelift)\n|File:1999-2000 Audi A3 (8L) 1.8 5-door hatchback 01.jpg|Audi A3 5-door (pre-facelift)\n|File:Audi A3 1.8 T (8L, Facelift) \u2013 Heckansicht, 29. Mai 2014, D\u00fcsseldorf.jpg|Audi A3 5-door (post-facelift)\n}}\n\n===Safety===\n{{Euro NCAP |align=left |year=1998 |description=Audi A3, 3dr hatchback |reference_url=http://www.euroncap.com/tests/audi_a3_1998/30.aspx |reference_name=EuroNCAPtest1 |adult_stars=4 |adult_score=25 |pedestrian_stars=2 |pedestrian_score=12}}\nEuro NCAP rating of 4 out of 5 stars.<ref name=EuroNCAPtest1/> Their evaluation concluded \"the column lock, adjuster lever and bracket presented hazards in the knee impact area for the driver. These could cause high loads on his upper legs and damage to his knees.\" The A3 also provides almost no protection to pedestrians, giving it two stars out of a possible four.<ref name=EuroNCAPtest1/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===S3 (1999\u20132003)===\n[[File:2000 Audi S3 (8L) quattro 3-door hatchback (2015-05-29) 01.jpg|thumb|left|Audi S3 (pre-facelift)]]\n[[File:Audi S3 2002 Imola Yellow.jpg|thumb|Audi S3 (facelift) finished in Imola Yellow|alt=]]\n[[File:2000 Audi S3 (8L) quattro 3-door hatchback (2015-05-29) 02.jpg|thumb|left|Audi S3 (pre-facelift)]]\n[[File:Audi S3 2002 Imola Yellow - Flickr - The Car Spy (1).jpg|thumb|right|Audi S3 (facelift)]]\n\nAudi released the A3-derived Audi S3 in 1999, only as a three-door hatchback. The inline-four [[multi-valve|20v]] 1.8&nbsp;L [[turbocharger|turbocharged]] [[petrol engine]] came in two versions: {{convert|210|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|225|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}. Early models (1999\u20132001) had {{convert|210|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}. Later models (2001\u20132003) had [[variable valve timing]] and {{convert|225|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}. The engine had a maximum of {{convert|280|Nm|ftlbf|abbr=on}} torque. This was the first time a small four-cylinder engine had been used in an [[Audi S and RS models#S models|Audi S-series]] car.\n\nAlthough dubbed [[quattro (four-wheel-drive system)|\"quattro\"]], the S3 uses a different [[four-wheel drive]] system.<ref name=\"autoportal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.carautoportal.com/audi/audi-s3.php|title=Audi S3|accessdate=28 June 2009|work=carautoportal.com|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090731142939/http://www.carautoportal.com/audi/audi-s3.php|archivedate=31 July 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Haldex Traction]] coupling adjusts the bias of torque distribution from the front to rear axle as grip requirements change \u2013 most of the time it operates as a front-wheel drive.\n\nThe S3 was sold in Europe, Japan, Mexico, South Africa, Australia, and New Zealand.\n\nThe S3 was given a facelift in 2002, where it was given one-piece headlights/indicator units, different front wings, rear lights clusters, and some minor upgrades to interior trim.\n\nStandard features include [[xenon HID headlamp]]s with high pressure washers and auto levelers, front fog lamps, 17\" \"Avus\" [[alloy wheel]]s with 225/45R17 tyres, electrically adjustable [[Recaro]] leather seats, climate control, alarm and electronic stability control with [[traction control system|traction control]].\n\nOptions include a [[Bose Corporation|Bose]] sound system, boot/trunk or in-dash mounted 6-disc [[CD changer]], [[metallic paint]], 18-inch 9-spoke RSTT wheels, glass sunroof, centre arm rest, privacy glass (B-pillar backwards), auto-dimming rear-view mirror, parking assist, luggage net, heated front seats, [[cruise control]], aluminium door mirror casings and part leather/[[alcantara (material)|Alcantara]] (blue/silver/yellow) combination seat coverings. These items are standard in some export markets.\n\n===Engines===\n{{unreferenced section|date=December 2018}}\nThe engines used are the same as those for many other cars in the [[Volkswagen Group]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%;\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\" background:#dcdcdc;\n!colspan=8|Petrol engines<ref name=\"AMS 8L\">{{cite web |title=Audi A3 8L Technische Daten zu allen Motorisierungen |url=https://www.auto-motor-und-sport.de/marken-modelle/audi/a3/8l/technische-daten/ |website=auto motor und sport |accessdate=9 August 2019 |language=de |date=14 March 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n! Name!! Type!! Engine code!! Output at rpm!! Torque at rpm!! 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h (0-62&nbsp;mph) time!! Top speed!! Years\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''1.6 8v'''||{{convert|1595|cc|cuin|0|abbr=on}} I4||AEH/AKL/APF||{{convert|101|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 5,600 rpm||{{convert|145|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} at 3,800 rpm||11.0 s||{{convert|188|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}||1996\u20132000\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''1.6 8v'''||{{convert|1595|cc|cuin|0|abbr=on}} I4||AVU/BFQ||{{convert|102|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 5,600 rpm||{{convert|148|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} at 3,800 rpm||10.9 s||{{convert|189|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}||2000\u20132003\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''1.8 20v'''||{{convert|1781|cc|cuin|0|abbr=on}} I4||AGN/APG||{{convert|125|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 6,000 rpm||{{convert|170|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} at 4,200 rpm||9.6 s||{{convert|202|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}||1996\u20132003\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''1.8 20vT'''||{{convert|178