=}} at 1,750\u20133,250&nbsp;rpm\n| 7.3&nbsp;s\n| {{cvt|230|kph||0|disp=br()}}\n| 6-spd manual\n| 6-spd S&nbsp;tronic\n|}\n\n{{notelist|group=\"Gen3 Eng\"}}\n\n=={{Anchor|Mk4}}Fourth generation (2020\u2013present)==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Audi A3 Mk4\n| model_years = 2021-present\n| production = May 2020-present\n| engine = {{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Inline-three petrol engine\n                 | 1.0 L [[List of Volkswagen Group petrol engines#CHYB|''EA211 CHYB'']] [[Turbocharger|turbo]]\n                 }}\n                 {{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Inline-four petrol [[Hybrid electric vehicle|hybrid]] engine\n                 | 1 = 1.4 L ''EA211'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] [[Turbocharger|t/c]] [[Variable displacement|ACDT]] [[PHEV]] System\n                 | 2 = 1.5 L ''EA211 Evo'' turbo I4 (mild hybrid)\n                 }}\n                 {{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Straight-five engine\n                 | 1 = 2.5 L I5 [[Turbo fuel stratified injection|TFSI]]\n                 }}\n                 {{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Inline-four diesel engine\n                 | 1 = 2.0 L ''[[List of Volkswagen Group diesel engines#2.0 R4 16v TDI CR 81-176kW|EA288 evo 4]]'' [[Turbodiesel|TDI]]\n                 }}\n| related = [[Volkswagen Golf Mk8]]<br/>[[SEAT Le\u00f3n#Fourth generation (2020\u2013present)|SEAT Le\u00f3n Mk4]]<br/>[[\u0160koda Octavia#Fourth generation (2020\u2013present)|\u0160koda Octavia Mk4]]\n| type = \n| wheelbase = Sportback: 2.64 meters (103.9 in).\n| length = Sportback: 4.34 meters (17.9 in).\n| platform = [[Volkswagen Group MQB platform]]\n| body_style = 5-door hatchback (Sportback)<br/>4-door sedan\n| width = Sportback: 1.82 meters (71.7 in).\n| height = \n| class = C-Segment\n}}\nThe new Audi A3 was due to be revealed at the [[Geneva Motor Show]] in March 2020. However, due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 virus pandemic]] and Switzerland's self-imposed limit on gatherings of over 1,000 people, the event was cancelled.<ref>http://www.agefi.com/home/entreprises/detail/edition/online/article/les-organisateurs-ont-decide-cette-apres-midi-de-lannulation-de-la-90e-edition-du-geneva-international-motor-show-la-manifestation-internationale-devait-debuter-la-semaine-prochaine-494486.html</ref> However, it was presented online, and also in Ingolstadt to be watched live. \n\nIt was presented on the Sportback version. It presented an all new styling, said by Audi to be inspired by [[Lamborghini]], LED headlights and taillights, with the option of Matrix LED headlights. It shares the MQB platform with some other Audi models, and with the [[Volkswagen Golf Mk8]], [[SEAT Le\u00f3n|SEAT Leon Mk4]], and [[\u0160koda Octavia|\u0160koda Octavia Mk4]]. The sedan body is expected to be presented in the months to come, with the 3 door hatchback unavailable, and the Cabriolet is still to be announced. \n\nIt is 3 centimeters longer and wider (now 4.34 and 1.82 meters) compared to the outgoing model, keeps the wheelbase length (2.64 meters now), trunk cargo space of 380 liters with the sits on, and 1200 litres with the seats folded. With drag coefficient of 0.28, powered by 1.5-liter gasoline turbocharged with option of mild hybrid (1.4-liter TSI + electric motor + six-speed automatic gearbox) with 150 [[Horsepower|HP]], 1.0-liter 3-cylinder with 110 HP, 2.0-liters [[TDI (engine)|TDI]] with 116 and 150 HP, or the RS3 with a 2.5 liter 5-cylinder with almost 400 HP. It gets a six-speed manual, seven-speed dual clutch automatic, or an electric [[Direct-shift gearbox|S-Tronic]] gearboxes.\nIt also gets the new MMI infotainment system, with a 10.25 to 12.3-inch digital instrument cluster, and a second screen of 10.1-inches that controls the other settings of the car.\n\n==Awards and accolades==\n* (2014) [[World Car of the Year]]\n* (2013) ''What Car?'' Small Family Car of the Year\n* (2013) ''[[What Car?]]'' Car of the Year<ref name=\"AV\">{{cite news|url=http://www.whatcar.com/car-news/why-the-audi-a3-is-car-of-the-year-2013/265021 |title=2013 COTY: Audi A3 |publisher=What Car? |author= |date=9 January 2013 |accessdate=9 January 2013 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130113052603/http://www.whatcar.com/car-news/why-the-audi-a3-is-car-of-the-year-2013/265021 |archivedate=13 January 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* (2006) South African Car of the Year\n* (2000) Brazilian Car of the Year\n* (1997, 1999, 2000) ''[[Auto motor und sport]]'' readers' poll Best Car award\n* (1997) ''[[Autozeitung]]'' \"Auto Trophy\" award\n* (1996) ''[[Bild am Sonntag]]'' \"Golden Steering Wheel\" award\n\n==Motorsport==\n{{unreferenced section|date=December 2018}}\n[[File:Mandie August-Audi S3.jpg|thumb|right|200px|An Audi S3 driven by [[Mandie August]] in the [[FIA European Rallycross Championship]]]]\n[[File:Audi RS3 LMS TCR (Antti Buri) (43327383880).jpg|thumb|left|200px|An Audi RS3 LMS TCR in the [[TCR International Series#ADAC TCR Germany Touring Car Championship|ADAC TCR Germany Touring Car Championship]] paddock]]\n[[File:Jean-Karl Vernay TCR Audi RS3.jpg|thumb|left|200px|An Audi RS3 LMS TCR in the [[TCR International Series#TCR Europe Series|TCR Europe Series]] paddock]]\n[[M\u00fcnnich Motorsport]] used an S3 in the [[FIA World Rallycross Championship]] and the [[FIA European Rallycross Championship]]\n\n[[Robb Holland]] used an S3 Saloon to compete in the [[2014 British Touring Car Championship season]] under the [[Next Generation Touring Car|NGTC regs]]. [[2017 British Touring Car Championship|Currently]] [[AmD Essex|AmD Tuning]] field two S3 Saloon's for [[Ant Whorton-Eales]] and [[Ollie Jackson]].\n\nIn 2016, Audi's motorsports brand, [[Audi Sport]] announced that it would be producing a RS3 LMS beginning in 2017. The car is built to [[TCR International Series]] regulations.\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n# \"A7, A5, and A3 Joins Even Numbers\", an article in the \"News\" section on page thirty-eight of the June, 2004 issue of ''[[Motor Trend]]''\n# Audi A3 Owner's Manual (English/UK edition) (2000 Audi AG)\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Audi A3}}\n\n*{{Official website|http://www.audi.com/en/models/a3.html|A3}} \u2013 official site at [[Audi]] worldwide\n*{{Official website|http://www.audi.in/in/web/en/models/a3/a3-sedan.html|A3}} \u2013 official site at [[Audi]] India\n\n{{Audi}}\n{{Audi (Europe) timeline 1970 to date}}\n{{Modern North American Audi vehicles}}\n\n[[Category:Audi vehicles|A3]]\n[[Category:Compact cars]]\n[[Category:Euro NCAP small family cars]]\n[[Category:Hatchbacks]]\n[[Category:Sedans]]\n[[Category:Station wagons]]\n[[Category:Convertibles]]\n[[Category:Front-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:All-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Cars powered by VR engines]]\n[[Category:Touring cars]]\n[[Category:Plug-in hybrid vehicles]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1996]]\n[[Category:2000s cars]]\n[[Category:2010s cars]]\n[[Category:2020s cars]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Audi A3\n| image = 2018 Audi A3 Sport TDi Saloon 1.5 Front.jpg\n| caption = The facelift 3rd generation Audi A3 Saloon (8V, UK)\n| manufacturer = [[Audi|Audi AG]]\n| production = 1996\u2013present\n| Designer = David Caffrey\n| class = [[Compact executive car|Subcompact executive car]] ([[C-segment|C]])\n| body_style = 3 or 5-door [[hatchback]]\n| layout = [[Front-engine, front-wheel-drive layout|Front-engine, front-wheel-drive]] / [[Front-engine, four-wheel-drive layout|four-wheel-drive]] ([[quattro (four-wheel-drive system)|quattro]])\n| platform = [[Volkswagen Group A platform]]<br/>[[Volkswagen Group MQB platform]]\n| transmission = \n| sp = uk\n| Engine = 3.2L V12\n}}\n\nThe '''Audi A3''' is a [[Small family car|small family]] or [[Compact executive car|subcompact executive car]] manufactured and marketed since the 1990s<ref>[https://www.audi-mediacenter.com/en/press-releases/audi-a3-a-model-of-success-two-decades-three-generations-7134 Audi A3 a model of success: Two decades, three generations\"] (2 December 2016).  ''Audi-MediaCenter.com''.  Retrieved 24 December 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.autoevolution.com/audi/a3/ \"Audi A3: Generations Timeline, Specs, and Pictures\"] (28 October 2016).  ''AutoEvolution.com''.  Retrieved 11 January 2020.</ref> by the Audi subdivision of the [[Volkswagen Group]], now in its 3rd generation.\n\nThe first two generations of the Audi A3 were based on the [[Volkswagen Group A platform]], which they share with the [[Audi TT]], [[Volkswagen Golf]], [[Volkswagen Caddy]], and [[Volkswagen Touran]], as well as [[SEAT Le\u00f3n]], [[SEAT Toledo]], and [[\u0160koda Octavia]].\n\nThe third-generation A3 uses the [[Volkswagen Group MQB platform]].\n\n=={{Anchor|Mk1|8L}}First generation (''Typ'' 8L; 1996\u20132003)==\n{{unreferenced section|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n|name = First generation (8L)\n|image = Audi_A3_front_20080326.jpg\n|caption = Audi A3 5-door (post-facelift)\n|aka =\n|production = 1996\u20132003\n|designer = [[Dirk van Braeckel]] (1992)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bentleymotors.com/world_of_bentley/exhibitions/an_unbroken_line_exhibition/the_team/ |title=Bentley Motors Website : World of Bentley : Exhibitions : 'An Unbroken Line' Exhibition : The Team |publisher=Bentleymotors.com |date= |accessdate=21 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/2005-05-29/dirk-van-braeckel |title=Dirk van Braeckel |publisher=Businessweek |date=29 May 2005 |accessdate=21 February 2013}}</ref>\n|assembly = {{Unbulleted list |Germany: [[Ingolstadt]] (1996\u20132003) |Brazil: [[Curitiba]] ([[Volkswagen do Brasil]], 2000\u20132006)}}\n|body_style = 3-door [[hatchback]]<br/>5-door [[hatchback]]\n|platform = [[Volkswagen Group A platform#PQ34|Volkswagen Group A4 (PQ34)]]\n|engine = Petrol engine<br/ >{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = I4\n|1 = [[List of discontinued Volkswagen Group petrol engines#1.6 R4 74-75kW|1.6]]&nbsp;L\n|2 = [[List of discontinued Volkswagen Group petrol engines#1.8 R4 20v 92kW|1.8]]&nbsp;L [[multi-valve|20v]]\n|3 = [[List of Volkswagen Group petrol engines#1.8 R4 20vT|1.8]]&nbsp;L 20v Turbo\n}}\nDiesel engine<br/ >{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Inline-four\n|1 = [[List of Volkswagen Group diesel engines#1.9 R4 TDI PD 43-118kW|1.9]]&nbsp;L [[Turbocharged Direct Injection|TDI]]\n}}\n|transmission ={{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Manual transmission \n|1 = 5-speed [[Manual transmission|Manual]]\n|2 = 6-speed [[Manual transmission|Manual]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Automatic transmission\n|1 = 4-speed [[Automatic transmission|Automatic]]\n|2 = 5-speed [[Automatic transmission|Automatic]]\n}}\n|wheelbase = A3 {{convert|2513|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<br/>quattro & S3: {{convert|2519|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|length = A3 {{convert|4152|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<br/>S3 {{convert|4159|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|width = A3 {{convert|1735|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<br/>S3 {{convert|1763|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|height = A3 {{convert|1423|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<br/>S3 {{convert|1415|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n|related = [[Volkswagen Golf#Golf Mk4 (A4/Typ 1J, 1997\u20132004)|Volkswagen Golf]] Mk4<br/>[[SEAT Le\u00f3n#1M|SEAT Le\u00f3n]] Mk1\n|sp = uk\n}}\n\nThe original A3 (or ''Type'' 8L) was introduced in the European market in 1996, marking Audi's return to the production of smaller cars following the demise of the [[Audi 50]] in 1978. This was the first [[Volkswagen Group]] model to use the \"PQ34\" or \"A4\" [[Automobile platform|platform]], bearing a close resemblance to the contemporary [[Volkswagen Golf Mk4]], which arrived a year later. Within three years, this platform was used for total of seven cars.\n\nThe A3 was initially available only with a three-door [[hatchback]] body, to present a more sporty image than the Golf, in both [[front-wheel drive|front]] and [[four-wheel drive]]. The [[inline-four engine|inline four-cylinder]] engines were [[transverse engine|transversely mounted]]. The Audi A3 was the eighth model in the Audi lineup to use five valves per cylinder.\n\nThe United Kingdom market first received the Audi A3 in November 1996.\n\nIn 1999, Audi expanded the range with the introduction of more powerful versions: a 1.8 turbo rated {{convert|180|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}, and a 1.9 [[Turbocharged Direct Injection|TDI]] [[diesel engine]] with [[unit injector]] \"Pumpe D\u00fcse\" (PD) technology and [[variable geometry turbocharger]]. The four-wheel-drive A3 1.8T [[quattro (four-wheel-drive system)|quattro]] used either the {{convert|150|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} or {{convert|180|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} engine, and the same [[Haldex Traction]]-based four-wheel-drive system as the [[Audi S3]] and the [[Audi TT]]. Also in 1999, Audi also introduced a five-door body.\n\nIn late 2000, the A3 range was revised with new headlights and rear lamps, other minor cosmetic changes, an improved interior, and the introduction of a six-speed [[manual transmission|manual]] gearbox, on the {{convert|180|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} 1.8 Turbo and the new {{convert|130|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} 1.9 TDI.\n\nAudi's [[electronic stability control]], traction-control, and brake force distribution computer became standard equipment in some countries.\n\nAlthough the first-generation Audi A3 was replaced in Europe in 2003, the first generation model continued to be sold in some markets. Production of the first generation model stopped in Brazil in 2006.\n\n{{gallery\n| width = 160\n| height = 100\n|File:1997 Audi A3 1.6 Front.jpg|Audi A3 3-door (pre-facelift)\n|File:1997 Audi A3 1.6 Rear.jpg|Audi A3 3-door (pre-facelift)\n|File:1999-2000 Audi A3 (8L) 1.8 5-door hatchback 01.jpg|Audi A3 5-door (pre-facelift)\n|File:Audi A3 1.8 T (8L, Facelift) \u2013 Heckansicht, 29. Mai 2014, D\u00fcsseldorf.jpg|Audi A3 5-door (post-facelift)\n}}\n\n===Safety===\n{{Euro NCAP |align=left |year=1998 |description=Audi A3, 3dr hatchback |reference_url=http://www.euroncap.com/tests/audi_a3_1998/30.aspx |reference_name=EuroNCAPtest1 |adult_stars=4 |adult_score=25 |pedestrian_stars=2 |pedestrian_score=12}}\nEuro NCAP rating of 4 out of 5 stars.<ref name=EuroNCAPtest1/> Their evaluation concluded \"the column lock, adjuster lever and bracket presented hazards in the knee impact area for the driver. These could cause high loads on his upper legs and damage to his knees.\" The A3 also provides almost no protection to pedestrians, giving it two stars out of a possible four.<ref name=EuroNCAPtest1/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===S3 (1999\u20132003)===\n[[File:2000 Audi S3 (8L) quattro 3-door hatchback (2015-05-29) 01.jpg|thumb|left|Audi S3 (pre-facelift)]]\n[[File:Audi S3 2002 Imola Yellow.jpg|thumb|Audi S3 (facelift) finished in Imola Yellow|alt=]]\n[[File:2000 Audi S3 (8L) quattro 3-door hatchback (2015-05-29) 02.jpg|thumb|left|Audi S3 (pre-facelift)]]\n[[File:Audi S3 2002 Imola Yellow - Flickr - The Car Spy (1).jpg|thumb|right|Audi S3 (facelift)]]\n\nAudi released the A3-derived Audi S3 in 1999, only as a three-door hatchback. The inline-four [[multi-valve|20v]] 1.8&nbsp;L [[turbocharger|turbocharged]] [[petrol engine]] came in two versions: {{convert|210|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|225|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}. Early models (1999\u20132001) had {{convert|210|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}. Later models (2001\u20132003) had [[variable valve timing]] and {{convert|225|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}. The engine had a maximum of {{convert|280|Nm|ftlbf|abbr=on}} torque. This was the first time a small four-cylinder engine had been used in an [[Audi S and RS models#S models|Audi S-series]] car.\n\nAlthough dubbed [[quattro (four-wheel-drive system)|\"quattro\"]], the S3 uses a different [[four-wheel drive]] system.<ref name=\"autoportal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.carautoportal.com/audi/audi-s3.php|title=Audi S3|accessdate=28 June 2009|work=carautoportal.com|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090731142939/http://www.carautoportal.com/audi/audi-s3.php|archivedate=31 July 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Haldex Traction]] coupling adjusts the bias of torque distribution from the front to rear axle as grip requirements change \u2013 most of the time it operates as a front-wheel drive.\n\nThe S3 was sold in Europe, Japan, Mexico, South Africa, Australia, and New Zealand.\n\nThe S3 was given a facelift in 2002, where it was given one-piece headlights/indicator units, different front wings, rear lights clusters, and some minor upgrades to interior trim.\n\nStandard features include [[xenon HID headlamp]]s with high pressure washers and auto levelers, front fog lamps, 17\" \"Avus\" [[alloy wheel]]s with 225/45R17 tyres, electrically adjustable [[Recaro]] leather seats, climate control, alarm and electronic stability control with [[traction control system|traction control]].\n\nOptions include a [[Bose Corporation|Bose]] sound system, boot/trunk or in-dash mounted 6-disc [[CD changer]], [[metallic paint]], 18-inch 9-spoke RSTT wheels, glass sunroof, centre arm rest, privacy glass (B-pillar backwards), auto-dimming rear-view mirror, parking assist, luggage net, heated front seats, [[cruise control]], aluminium door mirror casings and part leather/[[alcantara (material)|Alcantara]] (blue/silver/yellow) combination seat coverings. These items are standard in some export markets.\n\n===Engines===\n{{unreferenced section|date=December 2018}}\nThe engines used are the same as those for many other cars in the [[Volkswagen Group]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%;\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\" background:#dcdcdc;\n!colspan=8|Petrol engines<ref name=\"AMS 8L\">{{cite web |title=Audi A3 8L Technische Daten zu allen Motorisierungen |url=https:/