ion|TFSI]]\n                 }}\n                 {{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Inline-four diesel engine\n                 | 1 = 2.0 L ''[[List of Volkswagen Group diesel engines#2.0 R4 16v TDI CR 81-176kW|EA288 evo 4]]'' [[Turbodiesel|TDI]]\n                 }}\n| related = [[Volkswagen Golf Mk8]]<br/>[[SEAT Le\u00f3n#Fourth generation (2020\u2013present)|SEAT Le\u00f3n Mk4]]<br/>[[\u0160koda Octavia#Fourth generation (2020\u2013present)|\u0160koda Octavia Mk4]]\n| type = \n| wheelbase = Sportback: 2.64 meters (103.9 in).\n| length = Sportback: 4.34 meters (17.9 in).\n| platform = [[Volkswagen Group MQB platform]]\n| body_style = 5-door hatchback (Sportback)<br/>4-door sedan\n| width = Sportback: 1.82 meters (71.7 in).\n| height = \n| class = C-Segment\n}}\nThe new Audi A3 was due to be revealed at the [[Geneva Motor Show]] in March 2020. However, due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 virus pandemic]] and Switzerland's self-imposed limit on gatherings of over 1,000 people, the event was cancelled.<ref>http://www.agefi.com/home/entreprises/detail/edition/online/article/les-organisateurs-ont-decide-cette-apres-midi-de-lannulation-de-la-90e-edition-du-geneva-international-motor-show-la-manifestation-internationale-devait-debuter-la-semaine-prochaine-494486.html</ref> However, it was presented online, and also in Ingolstadt to be watched live. \n\nIt was presented on the Sportback version. It presented an all new styling, said by Audi to be inspired by [[Lamborghini]], LED headlights and taillights, with the option of Matrix LED headlights. It shares the MQB platform with some other Audi models, and with the [[Volkswagen Golf Mk8]], [[SEAT Le\u00f3n|SEAT Leon Mk4]], and [[\u0160koda Octavia|\u0160koda Octavia Mk4]]. The sedan body is expected to be presented in the months to come, with the 3 door hatchback unavailable, and the Cabriolet is still to be announced. \n\nIt is 3 centimeters longer and wider (now 4.34 and 1.82 meters) compared to the outgoing model, keeps the wheelbase length (2.64 meters now), trunk cargo space of 380 liters with the sits on, and 1200 litres with the seats folded. With drag coefficient of 0.28, powered by 1.5-liter gasoline turbocharged with option of mild hybrid (1.4-liter TSI + electric motor + six-speed automatic gearbox) with 150 [[Horsepower|HP]], 1.0-liter 3-cylinder with 110 HP, 2.0-liters [[TDI (engine)|TDI]] with 116 and 150 HP, or the RS3 with a 2.5 liter 5-cylinder with almost 400 HP. It gets a six-speed manual, seven-speed dual clutch automatic, or an electric [[Direct-shift gearbox|S-Tronic]] gearboxes.\nIt also gets the new MMI infotainment system, with a 10.25 to 12.3-inch digital instrument cluster, and a second screen of 10.1-inches that controls the other settings of the car.\n\n==Awards and accolades==\n* (2014) [[World Car of the Year]]\n* (2013) ''What Car?'' Small Family Car of the Year\n* (2013) ''[[What Car?]]'' Car of the Year<ref name=\"AV\">{{cite news|url=http://www.whatcar.com/car-news/why-the-audi-a3-is-car-of-the-year-2013/265021 |title=2013 COTY: Audi A3 |publisher=What Car? |author= |date=9 January 2013 |accessdate=9 January 2013 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130113052603/http://www.whatcar.com/car-news/why-the-audi-a3-is-car-of-the-year-2013/265021 |archivedate=13 January 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* (2006) South African Car of the Year\n* (2000) Brazilian Car of the Year\n* (1997, 1999, 2000) ''[[Auto motor und sport]]'' readers' poll Best Car award\n* (1997) ''[[Autozeitung]]'' \"Auto Trophy\" award\n* (1996) ''[[Bild am Sonntag]]'' \"Golden Steering Wheel\" award\n\n==Motorsport==\n{{unreferenced section|date=December 2018}}\n[[File:Mandie August-Audi S3.jpg|thumb|right|200px|An Audi S3 driven by [[Mandie August]] in the [[FIA European Rallycross Championship]]]]\n[[File:Audi RS3 LMS TCR (Antti Buri) (43327383880).jpg|thumb|left|200px|An Audi RS3 LMS TCR in the [[TCR International Series#ADAC TCR Germany Touring Car Championship|ADAC TCR Germany Touring Car Championship]] paddock]]\n[[File:Jean-Karl Vernay TCR Audi RS3.jpg|thumb|left|200px|An Audi RS3 LMS TCR in the [[TCR International Series#TCR Europe Series|TCR Europe Series]] paddock]]\n[[M\u00fcnnich Motorsport]] used an S3 in the [[FIA World Rallycross Championship]] and the [[FIA European Rallycross Championship]]\n\n[[Robb Holland]] used an S3 Saloon to compete in the [[2014 British Touring Car Championship season]] under the [[Next Generation Touring Car|NGTC regs]]. [[2017 British Touring Car Championship|Currently]] [[AmD Essex|AmD Tuning]] field two S3 Saloon's for [[Ant Whorton-Eales]] and [[Ollie Jackson]].\n\nIn 2016, Audi's motorsports brand, [[Audi Sport]] announced that it would be producing a RS3 LMS beginning in 2017. The car is built to [[TCR International Series]] regulations.\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n# \"A7, A5, and A3 Joins Even Numbers\", an article in the \"News\" section on page thirty-eight of the June, 2004 issue of ''[[Motor Trend]]''\n# Audi A3 Owner's Manual (English/UK edition) (2000 Audi AG)\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Audi A3}}\n\n*{{Official website|http://www.audi.com/en/models/a3.html|A3}} \u2013 official site at [[Audi]] worldwide\n*{{Official website|http://www.audi.in/in/web/en/models/a3/a3-sedan.html|A3}} \u2013 official site at [[Audi]] India\n\n{{Audi}}\n{{Audi (Europe) timeline 1970 to date}}\n{{Modern North American Audi vehicles}}\n\n[[Category:Audi vehicles|A3]]\n[[Category:Compact cars]]\n[[Category:Euro NCAP small family cars]]\n[[Category:Hatchbacks]]\n[[Category:Sedans]]\n[[Category:Station wagons]]\n[[Category:Convertibles]]\n[[Category:Front-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:All-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Cars powered by VR engines]]\n[[Category:Touring cars]]\n[[Category:Plug-in hybrid vehicles]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1996]]\n[[Category:2000s cars]]\n[[Category:2010s cars]]\n[[Category:2020s car